description.plain:
Sean Michael Leonard Anderson (born March 25, 1988), known professionally as Big Sean, is an American hip hop recording artist from Detroit, Michigan. Sean signed with Kanye West’s GOOD Music in 2007, Def Jam Recordings in 2008 and Roc Nation in 2014. After releasing several mixtapes, Sean released his debut album, Finally Famous, in 2011.

Fresh off one of the coldest features of the year on Drake’s “All Me,” Sean released his second studio album, Hall of Fame, on August 27, 2013. Sean’s third studio album, Dark Sky Paradise, was released in 2015 and earned him his first No. 1 studio album. The album featured hits like the banger “I Don’t Fuck With You”, which peaked at #11 and went quadruple platinum, and the Drake-assisted “Blessings”, which went double platinum.

TWENTY88, a group composed of Sean and Jhené Aiko, released a self-titled album on March 28th, 2016. The group was titled as such as both artists turned 28 during 2016, as both were born in 1988.

In February 2017, he dropped his fourth studio album, I Decided, which debuted at No. 1, becoming his second consecutive No. 1 album. The album featured the double-platinum hit “Bounce Back”. The song peaked at No. 6 on the Billboard 100, making it his highest charting song to date.

On December 8th of the same year, Big Sean and Metro Boomin combined for Sean’s fifth studio, and first collaborative album, Double Or Nothing.

He would later return with another studio album, Detroit 2, which serves as a sequel to his 2012 mixtape Detroit. Arguably his most acclaimed album to date, it contained a host of features, including Eminem, Travis Scott,  Lil Wayne, Young Thug, Post Malone, and more, and contained the ten-minute Friday Night Cypher, a ten-minute track featuring a collection of Detroit-based rappers. It became his third straight No. 1 album.

description.plain:
“Control” is a braggadocious attempt to revitalize the competitive spirit of the rap game.

Kendrick Lamar sent shockwaves across the internet with his verse that name-drops and takes no prisoners. His bold claims and aggressive spitting led to an onslaught of response tracks and interviews from rappers looking to prove themselves or inspired to step up their game.

The track was originally intended to be on Big Sean’s album, Hall of Fame, but was removed from the final tracklisting due to sample clearance issues.

description.plain:
“I Don’t Fuck With You” is the fourth track on Big Sean’s album Dark Sky Paradise. He released “I Don’t Fuck With You” following the announcement that he had signed to Jay Z’s Roc Nation management. He released the song via uknowbigsean.com, along with three other records.

The track reached #11 on the Billboard Hot 100, and #1 on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop chart.

While the song isn’t written specifically about his relationship with Naya Rivera, Sean did tell Complex Magazine that he wrote the last verse with her in mind.

description.plain:
“Bounce Back” is a song dedicated to Sean’s ability to rise above taking a Loss. The phrase “bounce back” comes from the idiom, “bounce back harder than before.”

In the song, Sean uses a bouncy flow to glide over the Metro Boomin, Smash David, and Yung Berg production.

This song dropped hours after Sean’s first single, “No More Interviews.”

The flow Sean uses on the first verse is similar to Drake’s flow on “6 Man.”

The beat in this song originally was produced by TM88 and Smash David and was used by Juicy J in his song Act. Then this beat travelled to Hitmaka and Metro Boomin. Metro made the outro for this song.

“Bounce Back” became certified gold in the United States on January 24, 2017.

description.plain:
On “No Favors,” Big Sean and Eminem reinforce the idea that, for them, standing on top of the rap game requires no help.

While it isn’t the first time the Detroit natives have teamed up, it is the first time Em has featured on a Big Sean track.  He disses Donald Trump for the second time, and targets media personality and Trump supporter Ann Coulter.

In a Beats 1 interview with Zane Lowe, Big Sean said of their collaboration:

[Eminem] was the only person I heard that could be on that song. It kinda reminded me of why I am such an Eminem fan. It reminded me of why I fell in love with Eminem’s work. He is unique, he’s special.

Despite not being a single, the song managed to debut on #22 on the Billboard Hot 100.

description.plain:
On this soulful ballad, Sean invites label mates Kanye West and John Legend along as he reflects on the positive influences in his life, the struggles he faced throughout his journey, and the influence his grandmother had on his life.

Sean spoke on her passing to Billboard:

In a selfish way, it was hard to say goodbye,“ Sean says, "but when I stepped back, I was happy she was free of the wheelchair and didn’t have to go through that.” Her death shrouded the making of the album; one song is dedicated to her. “It’s my darkest work, but it makes me happy because I put my heart into it,” he says. “I hope they can feel the sincerity, the honesty – this has more soul.

He also spoke to MTV News:


“I just lost my grandma, so, right before she passed, I wrote this song. A major part of the song is about her. She never got a chance to hear it. It’s just an emotional thing. And I’ve got my mom here with me.

I’m having a hard time accepting her death, but I must acknowledge my grandma’s life, a true hero,” Sean said in the post’s caption, which highlights her work as a black female Captain during World War II, a police officer, teacher and counselor.

It’s just a song that comes straight 100 percent from the heart, I hope people can enjoy it. And I really appreciate John Legend and Kanye West being a part of that.


Natasha Bedingfield sings uncredited background vocals.



When Sean originally wrote the song, the first verse was written from the perspective of President Barack Obama as a child and the second verse was from the perspective of Osama Bin Laden as a child.

description.plain:
First single from Sean’s the sophomore album, “Hall of Fame.” KeY Wane spoke with Complex about the making of the song:


I think I went out to L.A. He flew me out there to work on his mixtape and his album. This is like March or April, sometime around then. When I got to the studio, he had recorded a reference of a song. It was like, ‘Man I think this could be a really big song, make a beat to it.’ I was in the studio, and he texted me the voice memo, and I kept listening to it, and he was like, ‘Man, make it with this type of bounce. Make it like a really big song.’

I had recorded some steel drums over it, and that was the beginning. I had like a kick and some claps—this is like same-day everything. It was just forming ideas, me and him. He’s a great writer, and there were a lot of people in the studio. It was just bouncing ideas for the record. It was just a skeleton, and Sean was like, ‘Shit, let’s get some of Young Chop’s drums on here.’ He threw his 808s and some high-hats on it, and we kind of had a skeleton at that moment.

description.plain:
This is the third collaboration between Sean and his mentor, Kanye West – the first being “Glenwood”, and the second being “Marvin & Chardonnay” from Sean’s first studio album Finally Famous.

The song follows almost exactly the same formula as “Marvin & Chardonnay”; soul sample over hard drums, uplifting hook, Kanye’s bridge – the main difference is the third verse where the two MC’s trade bars Watch The Throne style.

Production was handled by Travi$ Scott, his protege WondaGurl, DJ Mano, Kanye West and OG Webbie. It’s safe to assume the beat was made a little while ago, as DJ Mano cut his ties with Ye and G.O.O.D Music in 2014.

description.plain:
In a similar fashion to how Eminem united with six Detroiters to celebrate Detroit on 2014’s “Detroit vs. Everybody,” Big Sean goes further on “Friday Night Cypher” and brings together fourteen Detroit natives—eleven rappers and three producers. Part of the song is also produced by Detroit 2’s executive producer Hit-Boy, who is the only artist on this song who doesn’t hail from Detroit.

In rap, a “cypher” refers to a gathering of rappers, usually taking turns freestyling. “Friday Night Cypher” runs through seven beat switches and brings together rappers with very different styles over a nearly ten-minute run-time. It is notable for uniting individuals who have previously had disagreements, notably Eminem, Royce and Tee Grizzley, which Big Sean addressed in an interview with Vulture:

It’s definitely a moment on the album where the city comes together, even people who are rumored to have misunderstandings and beef.

songs.title_with_featured: Voices In My Head / Stick to the Plan

description.plain:
Alternating between four flows in “Voices in My Head / Stick to the Plan,” Big Sean addresses his relationship with his subconscious mind – one that condemns his past mistakes and bad habits; consequently, motivating him to remain steadfast in the pursuit of his goals.

“Voices in My Head” finds Sean ruminating on behaviors he’s often failed to prevent and transitions into “Stick to the Plan,” the upbeat second verse succeeding it: the new cadence and subject matter completely work to oppose such earlier intonations of self-doubt and lethargy, illustrating a transition between feelings of shame and regret to those of motivation and dedication.

The conclusion of the track finds Big Sean’s introspection going into hyperdrive; detachedly regarding suicidal ideation as something he’d be capable of only temporarily dismissing, acknowledging the continuity of such intrusive thoughts with a positive resolve.

Hours before the song’s release, Sean expressed his desire to be single again, saying: “I never knew that I didn’t know how to be alone in life.”

description.plain:
“Living Single” surfaced online in July of 2016 and was reported as an unreleased track from Chance’s Coloring Book studio sessions. On December 17th Big Sean released the track officially, making it the third single from his fourth studio album, I Decided. He decided to release the final version of “Living Single” in celebration of “Bounce Back” reaching the Top 40 on the Billboard Hot 100.

https://twitter.com/BigSean/status/809980814796718080

Weeks after  Coloring Book’s release, Chance the Rapper sat down with Zane Lowe and mentioned that artists like Big Sean, Jeremih, and J. Cole had recorded music for the album; however, those tracks didn’t make the cut.

https://twitter.com/chancetherapper/status/755770755867111424

Big Sean had tweeted about “Living Single” after it leaked, claiming he planned to include it on his next album.

https://twitter.com/BigSean/status/755812098806996992?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw

songs.title: Deep Reverence

description.plain:
On “Deep Reverence,” Big Sean and the late Nipsey Hussle rap about pressures in life, both from gang violence, the rap game, and personal struggles. The track serves as the lead single to Sean’s fifth studio album, Detroit 2.

In February 2020, Sean addressed working together with Nipsey prior to his passing during an episode of Joe Budden’s Pull Up:

I was working on this song with Nip and then Nip passed…

Hit-Boy previewed the track in an Instagram live session with Boi-1da on March 28, 2020.

Sean released the song on August 25, 2020, by replying to a fan’s tweet the day before, saying that he felt “the world needs to hear [and] feel Nipsey presence!”

songs.title: Light

description.plain:
“Light” is about resiliency in the face of adversity. Big Sean contrasts his accomplishments with hardships like racial discrimination that drove him to succeed, and revels in his music’s influence—he shouts out Steph Curry and Lebron James, who both drew inspiration from his songs.

In a Tim Westwood interview, Sean said the titular “light” represents inner strength:

When you realize that your inner power is the key to everything on the outside—when you realize that you’ve got that light and you hold all the answers that you’ve been looking for in all these other places—then that’s the first step to really changing your whole world.

description.plain:
Big Sean’s and Post Malone’s first collaboration is a reflection on the environments the two artists grew up in. Sean draws a parallel between his family and wolves, implying dominance and loyalty to the pack. Big Sean detailed in an October 2019 interview with Entertainment Weekly:

[That song is about] my family growing up. Everybody’s in there, my grandma, my mom, my brother — it’s like they were a pack of wolves and they were the sweetest and strongest.

Sean revealed in the same interview that the track originally featured a verse from A$AP Rocky, but the guest appearance was later repurposed for another song on the album.

On September 29, 2019, producing duo Take A Daytrip previewed a snippet of the song via Instagram Live. Post Malone’s involvement in Detroit 2 was later hinted to in the album teaser.

description.plain:
The fourth single off Hall of Fame, with a music video featuring Miley Cyrus (also the verses are in a different order):

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=560v12-5yoQ&feature=kp

The sample is uncredited and it appears almost a year passed from the song’s release before anyone in the public identified it. The sample is “Kumpo (Senegal)” by Adzido, from a 2005 album of African music.
“Kumpo (Senagal)” on Spotify <–3:07 or 3:32

DJ Camper broke down the making of the beat in a video, where he explains the beat was intended for Kanye West because Camper thought the sample sounded like “Kanye, Kanye, Kanye”, but Kanye passed on the beat and also felt it sounded more like “Higher, higher, higher.” This means egotist Kanye West was told “Hey this sounds like people chanting your name,” and he disagreed. The beat was then used by Keri Hilson before it ended up the hands of Big Sean.
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L0bIqD5X5DE

A Rolling Stone article reveals Kanye told Sean to use this beat.

songs.title: Sunday Morning Jetpack

description.plain:
This mellow, and rhythmic song is a handful of Big Sean’s childhood memories and favorite times, like prom or eating his grandma’s home cooked meals being reminisced by him.

He calls these times “a oneway trip to paradise.” He talks about the struggles he goes through growing up and how they’ve made him who he is today. He uses his metaphorical jetpack to fly up in times of hardship within his family to get blessings and bring them down to them to stop the hardship.
